-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- JOHN CHAPTER 4 — The Woman at the Well and the Nobleman's Son
-- 54 verses · Greek text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 4,
  'John 4 records two transformative encounters that reveal Jesus as the Saviour of the world. Jesus leaves Judaea for Galilee and ''must needs go through Samaria'' (v.4). At Jacob''s well near Sychar, he meets a Samaritan woman at the sixth hour (noon). ''Give me to drink'' (v.7) — a Jewish rabbi breaking every social convention by speaking to a Samaritan, a woman, and one living in sin. She is astonished: ''How is it that thou, being a Jew, askest drink of me, which am a woman of Samaria?'' (v.9). Jesus redirects: ''If thou knewest the gift of God, and who it is that saith to thee, Give me to drink; thou wouldest have asked of him, and he would have given thee living water'' (v.10). She thinks physically; he speaks spiritually: ''Whosoever drinketh of this water shall thirst again: But whosoever drinketh of the water that I shall give him shall never thirst; but the water that I shall give him shall be in him a well of water springing up into everlasting life'' (vv.13-14). When she asks for this water, Jesus exposes her life: ''Thou hast had five husbands; and he whom thou now hast is not thy husband'' (v.18). She raises the worship question — ''Our fathers worshipped in this mountain'' (v.20). Jesus reveals: ''The hour cometh, and now is, when the true worshippers shall worship the Father in spirit and in truth'' (v.23). She mentions the coming Messiah. Jesus declares: ''I that speak unto thee am he'' (v.26). The woman becomes an evangelist: ''Come, see a man, which told me all things that ever I did: is not this the Christ?'' (v.29). Many Samaritans believe: ''Now we believe, not because of thy saying: for we have heard him ourselves, and know that this is indeed the Christ, the Saviour of the world'' (v.42). Meanwhile, Jesus teaches his disciples: ''My meat is to do the will of him that sent me'' (v.34) and ''Lift up your eyes, and look on the fields; for they are white already to harvest'' (v.35). The chapter closes with the second sign: the healing of the nobleman''s son at Capernaum from a distance — ''Thy son liveth'' (v.50) — and the whole household believes.',
  'Living Water, True Worship, and the Saviour of the World',
  'ὕδωρ ζῶν (hydōr zōn)',
  'Living water — hydōr (water, G5204) + zaō (to live, G2198). In the OT, ''living water'' (mayim chayyim) means flowing, fresh water from a spring, as opposed to stagnant cistern water (cf. Genesis 26:19; Leviticus 14:5; Jeremiah 2:13; 17:13; Zechariah 14:8). Jesus transforms the metaphor: the ''living water'' he gives is the Holy Spirit (7:38-39), the inner, inexhaustible spring of eternal life. Unlike physical water that temporarily satisfies, this water permanently quenches the deepest thirst of the human soul — the thirst for God himself.',
  '["Jesus Departs for Galilee through Samaria (vv.1-6): When the Lord knew the Pharisees had heard that Jesus made and baptized more disciples than John (though Jesus himself baptized not but his disciples) he left Judaea and departed again into Galilee. He must needs go through Samaria. He cometh to a city of Samaria called Sychar near the parcel of ground that Jacob gave to Joseph. Now Jacob''s well was there. Jesus therefore being wearied with his journey sat thus on the well — it was about the sixth hour","Give Me to Drink — The Living Water (vv.7-15): There cometh a woman of Samaria to draw water. Jesus saith — Give me to drink. The woman saith — How is it that thou being a Jew askest drink of me a Samaritan? Jesus answered — If thou knewest the gift of God and who it is that saith Give me to drink thou wouldest have asked of him and he would have given thee living water. Art thou greater than our father Jacob? Whosoever drinketh of this water shall thirst again but whosoever drinketh of the water that I shall give him shall never thirst — it shall be in him a well of water springing up into everlasting life. The woman saith — Sir give me this water that I thirst not","Go Call Thy Husband — The Prophet Revealed (vv.16-20): Jesus saith — Go call thy husband and come hither. The woman answered — I have no husband. Jesus said — Thou hast well said. Thou hast had five husbands and he whom thou now hast is not thy husband. The woman saith — Sir I perceive that thou art a prophet. Our fathers worshipped in this mountain and ye say that in Jerusalem is the place where men ought to worship","Worship in Spirit and in Truth (vv.21-26): Jesus saith — Woman believe me the hour cometh when ye shall neither in this mountain nor yet at Jerusalem worship the Father. Ye worship ye know not what — we know what we worship for salvation is of the Jews. But the hour cometh and now is when the true worshippers shall worship the Father in spirit and in truth. God is a Spirit and they that worship him must worship him in spirit and in truth. The woman saith — I know that Messias cometh which is called Christ — when he is come he will tell us all things. Jesus saith — I that speak unto thee am he","The Harvest and the Disciples'' Return (vv.27-38): His disciples came and marvelled that he talked with the woman yet no man said What seekest thou or Why talkest thou with her? The woman left her waterpot and went into the city — Come see a man which told me all things that ever I did — is not this the Christ? In the mean while his disciples prayed him saying Master eat. He said — I have meat to eat that ye know not of. My meat is to do the will of him that sent me and to finish his work. Lift up your eyes and look on the fields for they are white already to harvest. He that reapeth receiveth wages and gathereth fruit unto life eternal — that both he that soweth and he that reapeth may rejoice together. I sent you to reap that whereon ye bestowed no labour — other men laboured and ye are entered into their labours","Many Samaritans Believe: The Saviour of the World (vv.39-42): Many of the Samaritans of that city believed on him for the saying of the woman — He told me all that ever I did. They besought him to tarry and he abode there two days. Many more believed because of his own word. They said unto the woman — Now we believe not because of thy saying for we have heard him ourselves and know that this is indeed the Christ the Saviour of the world","The Second Sign: The Nobleman''s Son Healed (vv.43-54): After two days he departed into Galilee. Jesus himself testified that a prophet hath no honour in his own country. The Galileans received him having seen the things he did at Jerusalem at the feast. He came again into Cana where he made the water wine. A certain nobleman whose son was sick at Capernaum went unto him — Come down ere my child die. Jesus saith — Go thy way thy son liveth. The man believed the word and went. His servants met him saying Thy son liveth. The fever left him at the seventh hour. The father knew it was the same hour Jesus said Thy son liveth — and himself believed and his whole house. This is again the second miracle that Jesus did when he was come out of Judaea into Galilee"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'John';

-- Step 2: Insert all 54 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'When therefore the Lord knew how the Pharisees had heard that Jesus made and baptized more disciples than John,',
   'ὡς οὖν ἔγνω ὁ Κύριος ὅτι ἤκουσαν οἱ Φαρισαῖοι ὅτι Ἰησοῦς πλείονας μαθητὰς ποιεῖ καὶ βαπτίζει ἢ Ἰωάννης',
   'hōs oun egnō ho Kyrios hoti ēkousan hoi Pharisaioi hoti Iēsous pleionas mathētas poiei kai baptizei ē Iōannēs',
   '''The Lord'' (ho Kyrios — John uses the title ''Lord'' here, reflecting the post-resurrection perspective of the Evangelist). Jesus withdraws from Judaea not from fear but from strategic timing — his ''hour'' has not yet come (2:4; 7:30). The Pharisees'' attention is a sign that confrontation is premature.',
   NULL),
  (2, '(Though Jesus himself baptized not, but his disciples,)',
   'καίτοιγε Ἰησοῦς αὐτὸς οὐκ ἐβάπτιζεν ἀλλ᾽ οἱ μαθηταὶ αὐτοῦ',
   'kaitoige Iēsous autos ouk ebaptizen all hoi mathētai autou',
   'A parenthetical clarification correcting 3:22: Jesus authorised and oversaw the baptising, but his disciples performed the actual immersions. This distinction preserves the uniqueness of the baptism Jesus would later institute (Matthew 28:19) and the baptism of the Spirit (John 1:33; Acts 1:5).',
   NULL),
  (3, 'He left Judaea, and departed again into Galilee.',
   'ἀφῆκεν τὴν Ἰουδαίαν καὶ ἀπῆλθεν πάλιν εἰς τὴν Γαλιλαίαν',
   'aphēken tēn Ioudaian kai apēlthen palin eis tēn Galilaian',
   'Jesus leaves Judaea for Galilee — the reverse of the usual pilgrimage route. The journey will take him through Samaria, setting the stage for the most unlikely of encounters.',
   NULL),
  (4, 'And he must needs go through Samaria.',
   'ἔδει δὲ αὐτὸν διέρχεσθαι διὰ τῆς Σαμαρείας',
   'edei de auton dierchesthai dia tēs Samareias',
   '''He must needs'' (edei — it was necessary, divinely ordained). While the most direct route from Judaea to Galilee passed through Samaria, many Jews took a longer route via Perea to avoid Samaritan territory. Jesus'' ''must'' is not geographical necessity but divine appointment — the Father is directing him to this woman. The same dei (divine necessity) governs the entire Gospel: he ''must'' be born again (3:7), ''must'' be lifted up (3:14), ''must'' go through Samaria (4:4).',
   NULL),
  (5, 'Then cometh he to a city of Samaria, which is called Sychar, near to the parcel of ground that Jacob gave to his son Joseph.',
   'ἔρχεται οὖν εἰς πόλιν τῆς Σαμαρείας λεγομένην Συχάρ πλησίον τοῦ χωρίου ὃ ἔδωκεν Ἰακὼβ Ἰωσὴφ τῷ υἱῷ αὐτοῦ',
   'erchetai oun eis polin tēs Samareias legomenēn Sychar plēsion tou chōriou ho edōken Iakōb Iōsēph tō huiō autou',
   '''Sychar'' — likely the modern village of Askar, near ancient Shechem, at the foot of Mount Ebal. ''The parcel of ground that Jacob gave to his son Joseph'' (cf. Genesis 33:19; 48:22; Joshua 24:32). The OT allusions are rich: Jacob, the well, the land, Joseph — all point to covenant history. Jesus stands on patriarchal ground, about to offer something greater than the patriarch could give.',
   NULL),
  (6, 'Now Jacob''s well was there. Jesus therefore, being wearied with his journey, sat thus on the well: and it was about the sixth hour.',
   'ἦν δὲ ἐκεῖ πηγὴ τοῦ Ἰακώβ ὁ οὖν Ἰησοῦς κεκοπιακὼς ἐκ τῆς ὁδοιπορίας ἐκαθέζετο οὕτως ἐπὶ τῇ πηγῇ ὥρα ἦν ὡσεὶ ἕκτη',
   'ēn de ekei pēgē tou Iakōb ho oun Iēsous kekopiakōs ek tēs hodoiporias ekathezeto houtōs epi tē pēgē hōra ēn hōsei hektē',
   '''Being wearied'' (kekopiakōs — having been exhausted, fatigued; perfect participle: thoroughly tired). A vivid detail affirming the true humanity of the incarnate Word (cf. 1:14). The Logos who created all things (1:3) sits weary at a well. ''Sat thus on the well'' (ekathezeto houtōs — sat down just as he was, without ceremony). ''The sixth hour'' — noon by Jewish reckoning (or 6 PM by Roman; most scholars prefer noon). An unusual time for drawing water, suggesting the woman avoids the morning crowd — perhaps due to her reputation.',
   NULL),
  (7, 'There cometh a woman of Samaria to draw water: Jesus saith unto her, Give me to drink.',
   'ἔρχεται γυνὴ ἐκ τῆς Σαμαρείας ἀντλῆσαι ὕδωρ λέγει αὐτῇ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Δός μοι πιεῖν',
   'erchetai gynē ek tēs Samareias antlēsai hydōr legei autē ho Iēsous Dos moi piein',
   '''A woman of Samaria'' (gynē ek tēs Samareias — a Samaritan woman). Jesus initiates the conversation — breaking multiple social boundaries: Jews did not associate with Samaritans (v.9), rabbis did not speak publicly with women, and this woman''s moral reputation adds another layer. ''Give me to drink'' (dos moi piein — give me something to drink; aorist imperative). Jesus makes himself vulnerable, asking for help — a masterful pastoral approach that opens dialogue.',
   NULL),
  (8, '(For his disciples were gone away unto the city to buy meat.)',
   'οἱ γὰρ μαθηταὶ αὐτοῦ ἀπεληλύθεισαν εἰς τὴν πόλιν ἵνα τροφὰς ἀγοράσωσιν',
   'hoi gar mathētai autou apelēlytheisan eis tēn polin hina trophas agorasōsin',
   'A parenthetical explanation: the disciples had gone to buy food, leaving Jesus alone — the divine appointment is set. The disciples'' willingness to buy food in a Samaritan city suggests some openness, though their surprise at Jesus talking with the woman (v.27) shows lingering prejudice.',
   NULL),
  (9, 'Then saith the woman of Samaria unto him, How is it that thou, being a Jew, askest drink of me, which am a woman of Samaria? for the Jews have no dealings with the Samaritans.',
   'λέγει οὖν αὐτῷ ἡ γυνὴ ἡ Σαμαρεῖτις Πῶς σὺ Ἰουδαῖος ὢν παρ᾽ ἐμοῦ πιεῖν αἰτεῖς οὔσης γυναικὸς Σαμαρείτιδος οὐ γὰρ συγχρῶνται Ἰουδαῖοι Σαμαρείταις',
   'legei oun autō hē gynē hē Samareis Pōs sy Ioudaios ōn par emou piein aiteis ousēs gynaikos Samareitidos ou gar synchrōntai Ioudaioi Samareitais',
   '''Jews have no dealings with Samaritans'' (ou synchrōntai — do not use together, do not share vessels with). The Jewish-Samaritan hostility had centuries of history: the Samaritans were descended from the intermarriage of Israelites with Assyrian colonists after 722 BC (2 Kings 17:24-41). They accepted only the Pentateuch, worshipped on Mount Gerizim, and were considered unclean by Jews. The woman is doubly marginalised: Samaritan and female.',
   NULL),
  (10, 'Jesus answered and said unto her, If thou knewest the gift of God, and who it is that saith to thee, Give me to drink; thou wouldest have asked of him, and he would have given thee living water.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς καὶ εἶπεν αὐτῇ Εἰ ᾔδεις τὴν δωρεὰν τοῦ θεοῦ καὶ τίς ἐστιν ὁ λέγων σοι Δός μοι πιεῖν σὺ ἂν ᾔτησας αὐτὸν καὶ ἔδωκεν ἄν σοι ὕδωρ ζῶν',
   'apekrithē Iēsous kai eipen autē Ei ēdeis tēn dōrean tou theou kai tis estin ho legōn soi Dos moi piein sy an ētēsas auton kai edōken an soi hydōr zōn',
   '''The gift of God'' (tēn dōrean tou theou — the free gift, the gracious gift of God). ''Who it is'' (tis estin — who is the one). Two things she does not know: (1) the gift God is offering, and (2) the identity of the one offering it. ''Living water'' (hydōr zōn — flowing, spring water; but Jesus means the water of eternal life, the Holy Spirit: 7:38-39). The irony is magnificent: she holds the bucket, but he holds the water that truly satisfies. He came asking for water; he is actually offering it.',
   'Jesus introduces two crucial concepts: (1) ''The gift of God'' — salvation is a gift (dōrea), not a reward, not earned. This is consistent with the entire Gospel witness: ''God so loved... that he gave'' (3:16); ''the gift of God is eternal life'' (Romans 6:23). (2) ''Living water'' — in the OT, God is called ''the fountain of living waters'' (Jeremiah 2:13; 17:13). To forsake God is to forsake ''living waters'' and dig ''broken cisterns'' (Jeremiah 2:13). Jesus claims to give what only God can give — the water of life. This is an implicit claim to deity.'),
  (11, 'The woman saith unto him, Sir, thou hast nothing to draw with, and the well is deep: from whence then hast thou that living water?',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ ἡ γυνή Κύριε οὔτε ἄντλημα ἔχεις καὶ τὸ φρέαρ ἐστὶν βαθύ πόθεν οὖν ἔχεις τὸ ὕδωρ τὸ ζῶν',
   'legei autō hē gynē Kyrie oute antlēma echeis kai to phrear estin bathy pothen oun echeis to hydōr to zōn',
   '''Sir'' (Kyrie — Lord/Sir; a respectful address, she does not yet know who he is). ''Nothing to draw with'' (oute antlēma echeis — you have no bucket). ''The well is deep'' (to phrear estin bathy — the well is deep; Jacob''s well is about 100 feet deep). ''From whence?'' (pothen) — a Johannine keyword: ''whence'' the wine came (2:9), ''whence'' Jesus comes (7:27-28; 8:14; 9:29-30; 19:9). The question is more profound than she knows: the living water comes ''from above'' (anōthen, 3:3, 31).',
   NULL),
  (12, 'Art thou greater than our father Jacob, which gave us the well, and drank thereof himself, and his children, and his cattle?',
   'μὴ σὺ μείζων εἶ τοῦ πατρὸς ἡμῶν Ἰακώβ ὃς ἔδωκεν ἡμῖν τὸ φρέαρ καὶ αὐτὸς ἐξ αὐτοῦ ἔπιεν καὶ οἱ υἱοὶ αὐτοῦ καὶ τὰ θρέμματα αὐτοῦ',
   'mē sy meizōn ei tou patros hēmōn Iakōb hos edōken hēmin to phrear kai autos ex autou epien kai hoi huioi autou kai ta thremmata autou',
   '''Art thou greater than our father Jacob?'' (mē sy meizōn ei — the mē expects a negative answer: ''You aren''t greater than Jacob, are you?''). But Johannine irony again: the answer is emphatically yes — Jesus is infinitely greater than Jacob. Jacob gave a well of physical water; Jesus gives the water of eternal life. ''Our father Jacob'' — the Samaritans claimed descent from the patriarchs through Joseph (via Ephraim and Manasseh). The question echoes 8:53: ''Art thou greater than our father Abraham?'' Both questions receive the same answer: yes.',
   NULL),
  (13, 'Jesus answered and said unto her, Whosoever drinketh of this water shall thirst again:',
   'ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς καὶ εἶπεν αὐτῇ Πᾶς ὁ πίνων ἐκ τοῦ ὕδατος τούτου διψήσει πάλιν',
   'apekrithē Iēsous kai eipen autē Pas ho pinōn ek tou hydatos toutou dipsēsei palin',
   '''Whosoever drinketh'' (pas ho pinōn — everyone who drinks; present participle: habitual drinking). ''Shall thirst again'' (dipsēsei palin — will become thirsty again). Physical water, physical satisfaction, worldly pleasures — they all leave the soul thirsty again. The well of this world can never permanently satisfy the deepest human need. This is the universal human experience: every earthly satisfaction is temporary.',
   NULL),
  (14, 'But whosoever drinketh of the water that I shall give him shall never thirst; but the water that I shall give him shall be in him a well of water springing up into everlasting life.',
   'ὃς δ᾽ ἂν πίῃ ἐκ τοῦ ὕδατος οὗ ἐγὼ δώσω αὐτῷ οὐ μὴ διψήσῃ εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα ἀλλὰ τὸ ὕδωρ ὃ δώσω αὐτῷ γενήσεται ἐν αὐτῷ πηγὴ ὕδατος ἁλλομένου εἰς ζωὴν αἰώνιον',
   'hos d an piē ek tou hydatos hou egō dōsō autō ou mē dipsēsei eis ton aiōna alla to hydōr ho dōsō autō genēsetai en autō pēgē hydatos hallomenou eis zōēn aiōnion',
   '''Shall never thirst'' (ou mē dipsēsei eis ton aiōna — emphatic double negative: will never, ever thirst into the age). ''A well of water'' (pēgē hydatos — a spring, fountain; not a stagnant cistern but a living, flowing source). ''Springing up'' (hallomenou — leaping up, gushing, overflowing; the same word describes the lame man leaping in Acts 3:8). ''Into everlasting life'' (eis zōēn aiōnion — issuing in, leading to eternal life). The living water is an internal, inexhaustible, self-renewing spring — the Holy Spirit indwelling the believer (7:38-39). The contrast is total: external vs. internal, temporary vs. permanent, physical vs. spiritual.',
   'The living water Jesus promises is identified in 7:38-39 as the Holy Spirit. The imagery combines several OT promises: (1) God as the ''fountain of living waters'' (Jeremiah 2:13). (2) The river flowing from the temple (Ezekiel 47:1-12). (3) ''With joy shall ye draw water out of the wells of salvation'' (Isaiah 12:3). (4) ''I will pour water upon him that is thirsty'' (Isaiah 44:3). The promise is radical: believers do not merely receive water from an external source but become themselves a spring — the indwelling Spirit produces continuous, overflowing life. This is the new birth (3:5) experienced from within.'),
  (15, 'The woman saith unto him, Sir, give me this water, that I thirst not, neither come hither to draw.',
   'λέγει πρὸς αὐτὸν ἡ γυνή Κύριε δός μοι τοῦτο τὸ ὕδωρ ἵνα μὴ διψῶ μηδὲ ἔρχωμαι ἐνθάδε ἀντλεῖν',
   'legei pros auton hē gynē Kyrie dos moi touto to hydōr hina mē dipsō mēde erchōmai enthade antlein',
   'The woman still thinks on the physical level — she wants water that eliminates the daily chore of drawing. Like Nicodemus (3:4), she cannot yet grasp the spiritual reality behind Jesus'' words. Yet her request is unwittingly profound: she is asking the right person for the right thing, even if she does not yet understand what she is asking for. Jesus will now redirect the conversation to expose her need.',
   NULL),
  (16, 'Jesus saith unto her, Go, call thy husband, and come hither.',
   'λέγει αὐτῇ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ὕπαγε φώνησον τὸν ἄνδρα σου καὶ ἐλθὲ ἐνθάδε',
   'legei autē ho Iēsous Hypage phōnēson ton andra sou kai elthe enthade',
   '''Go, call thy husband'' — an abrupt shift. Jesus is not changing the subject but deepening it: before she can receive living water, she must face the truth about her life. The command exposes her real thirst — not for water but for love, belonging, meaning. Her five failed marriages and current illicit relationship reveal a soul trying to fill an emptiness that only God can satisfy.',
   NULL),
  (17, 'The woman answered and said, I have no husband. Jesus said unto her, Thou hast well said, I have no husband:',
   'ἀπεκρίθη ἡ γυνὴ καὶ εἶπεν Οὐκ ἔχω ἄνδρα λέγει αὐτῇ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Καλῶς εἶπας ὅτι Ἄνδρα οὐκ ἔχω',
   'apekrithē hē gynē kai eipen Ouk echō andra legei autē ho Iēsous Kalōs eipas hoti Andra ouk echō',
   '''I have no husband'' (ouk echō andra — a carefully evasive answer that is technically true but deliberately incomplete). ''Thou hast well said'' (kalōs eipas — you have spoken rightly). Jesus commends her truthfulness while about to reveal the whole truth she is hiding. His response is neither condemning nor sarcastic but gently penetrating — he affirms what is true in her statement before exposing what is concealed.',
   NULL),
  (18, 'For thou hast had five husbands; and he whom thou now hast is not thy husband: in that saidst thou truly.',
   'πέντε γὰρ ἄνδρας ἔσχες καὶ νῦν ὃν ἔχεις οὐκ ἔστιν σου ἀνήρ τοῦτο ἀληθὲς εἴρηκας',
   'pente gar andras esches kai nyn hon echeis ouk estin sou anēr touto alēthes eirēkas',
   '''Five husbands'' (pente andras esches — you have had five men/husbands). ''He whom thou now hast is not thy husband'' — she is living with a man outside of marriage. Jesus demonstrates the supernatural knowledge affirmed in 2:24-25 (''he knew what was in man''). He does not condemn or lecture but simply states the truth — the light exposes (3:20-21) without destroying. Some commentators see a symbolic allusion to the five foreign deities brought to Samaria (2 Kings 17:30-31), but the literal reading is more natural and more pastorally powerful.',
   NULL),
  (19, 'The woman saith unto him, Sir, I perceive that thou art a prophet.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ ἡ γυνή Κύριε θεωρῶ ὅτι προφήτης εἶ σύ',
   'legei autō hē gynē Kyrie theōrō hoti prophētēs ei sy',
   '''I perceive'' (theōrō — I see, I observe, I am beginning to understand). ''A prophet'' (prophētēs) — her understanding is growing: from ''a Jew'' (v.9) to ''Sir'' (v.11) to ''a prophet'' (v.19) and finally to ''the Christ'' (v.29). The Samaritans expected a prophet like Moses (Deuteronomy 18:15-18), whom they called the Taheb (the ''Restorer'' or ''Returning One''). She is moving in the right direction but has not yet arrived at full understanding.',
   NULL),
  (20, 'Our fathers worshipped in this mountain; and ye say, that in Jerusalem is the place where men ought to worship.',
   'οἱ πατέρες ἡμῶν ἐν τῷ ὄρει τούτῳ προσεκύνησαν καὶ ὑμεῖς λέγετε ὅτι ἐν Ἱεροσολύμοις ἐστὶν ὁ τόπος ὅπου δεῖ προσκυνεῖν',
   'hoi pateres hēmōn en tō orei toutō prosekynēsan kai hymeis legete hoti en Hierosolymois estin ho topos hopou dei proskynein',
   '''This mountain'' — Mount Gerizim, visible from Jacob''s well, where the Samaritans had built their temple (destroyed by John Hyrcanus in 128 BC but still considered their holy site). The Jerusalem-vs-Gerizim debate was the central issue dividing Jews and Samaritans. The woman may be deflecting from the personal exposure of vv.17-18, but the question is also genuinely important: where is the right place to worship God?',
   NULL),
  (21, 'Jesus saith unto her, Woman, believe me, the hour cometh, when ye shall neither in this mountain, nor yet at Jerusalem, worship the Father.',
   'λέγει αὐτῇ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Γύναι πίστευσόν μοι ὅτι ἔρχεται ὥρα ὅτε οὔτε ἐν τῷ ὄρει τούτῳ οὔτε ἐν Ἱεροσολύμοις προσκυνήσετε τῷ πατρί',
   'legei autē ho Iēsous Gynai pisteuson moi hoti erchetai hōra hote oute en tō orei toutō oute en Hierosolymois proskynēsete tō patri',
   '''Believe me'' (pisteuson moi — trust me; aorist imperative: make a decision to believe). ''The hour cometh'' (erchetai hōra — an hour is coming). Jesus transcends both positions: neither Gerizim nor Jerusalem will be the exclusive place of worship. The coming ''hour'' brings a revolution in worship — it will no longer be tied to a location but to a person. ''The Father'' (tō patri) — Jesus introduces God as ''Father'' to this Samaritan woman, a term of intimate relationship rather than distant deity.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'Ye worship ye know not what: we know what we worship: for salvation is of the Jews.',
   'ὑμεῖς προσκυνεῖτε ὃ οὐκ οἴδατε ἡμεῖς προσκυνοῦμεν ὃ οἴδαμεν ὅτι ἡ σωτηρία ἐκ τῶν Ἰουδαίων ἐστίν',
   'hymeis proskyneite ho ouk oidate hēmeis proskynomen ho oidamen hoti hē sōtēria ek tōn Ioudaiōn estin',
   '''Ye worship ye know not what'' — the Samaritans, having rejected all Scripture beyond the Pentateuch, had an incomplete revelation. ''We know what we worship'' — Jesus identifies himself with Judaism (''we'') in terms of revelation history. ''Salvation is of the Jews'' (hē sōtēria ek tōn Ioudaiōn estin — salvation comes from, originates from the Jews). The Messiah, the Scriptures, the covenants, the promises — all come through Israel (Romans 9:4-5). This does not mean salvation is limited to Jews, but that God''s saving plan flows through the Jewish nation to the world.',
   NULL),
  (23, 'But the hour cometh, and now is, when the true worshippers shall worship the Father in spirit and in truth: for the Father seeketh such to worship him.',
   'ἀλλ᾽ ἔρχεται ὥρα καὶ νῦν ἐστιν ὅτε οἱ ἀληθινοὶ προσκυνηταὶ προσκυνήσουσιν τῷ πατρὶ ἐν πνεύματι καὶ ἀληθείᾳ καὶ γὰρ ὁ πατὴρ τοιούτους ζητεῖ τοὺς προσκυνοῦντας αὐτόν',
   'all erchetai hōra kai nyn estin hote hoi alēthinoi proskynētai proskynēsousin tō patri en pneumati kai alētheia kai gar ho patēr toioutous zētei tous proskynountas auton',
   '''The hour cometh, and now is'' (erchetai hōra kai nyn estin — the hour is both coming and already present; the ''already but not yet'' of Jesus'' ministry). ''True worshippers'' (hoi alēthinoi proskynētai — genuine, authentic worshippers; alēthinos means ''real'' as opposed to ''shadow''). ''In spirit and in truth'' (en pneumati kai alētheia) — worship that is Spirit-empowered (not merely external ritual) and truth-grounded (not ignorant or false). ''The Father seeketh'' (ho patēr zētei — the Father actively seeks, searches for). A stunning revelation: God is not passively waiting to be found but actively seeking worshippers. The Creator pursues the creature.',
   'This verse revolutionises the concept of worship: (1) ''In spirit'' — worship is no longer tied to a physical location (temple, mountain) but is enabled by the Holy Spirit and engages the human spirit. External ritual without internal reality is not true worship. (2) ''In truth'' — worship must be based on true knowledge of God as he has revealed himself, not on ignorance (v.22) or falsehood. The Samaritans worshipped in sincerity but not in full truth; the Jews had the truth but often lacked spiritual reality. True worship requires both. (3) ''The Father seeketh'' — the most remarkable statement: God is a seeking God. He seeks worshippers — not because he needs worship but because he desires relationship. This connects to the seeking shepherd (Luke 15:4), the seeking woman (Luke 15:8), and the seeking father (Luke 15:20).'),
  (24, 'God is a Spirit: and they that worship him must worship him in spirit and in truth.',
   'πνεῦμα ὁ θεός καὶ τοὺς προσκυνοῦντας αὐτὸν ἐν πνεύματι καὶ ἀληθείᾳ δεῖ προσκυνεῖν',
   'pneuma ho theos kai tous proskynountas auton en pneumati kai alētheia dei proskynein',
   '''God is a Spirit'' (pneuma ho theos — Spirit [is] God; the predicate ''Spirit'' comes first for emphasis). This is one of four great ''God is'' statements in John''s writings: ''God is Spirit'' (4:24), ''God is light'' (1 John 1:5), ''God is love'' (1 John 4:8, 16). God''s nature as Spirit means he is not confined to any location, cannot be contained in any building, and is not limited to any form. ''Must'' (dei — it is necessary, divinely required). The nature of God determines the nature of worship: because God is Spirit, worship must be spiritual; because God is truth, worship must be truthful.',
   'The declaration ''God is Spirit'' is foundational for all theology and worship. (1) God is not material — he has no body, no physical form, no spatial limitation (though he may manifest himself in physical ways, as in the Incarnation). (2) God is omnipresent — he cannot be confined to Gerizim or Jerusalem. (3) Worship that matches God''s nature must be ''in spirit'' (spiritual, not merely physical) and ''in truth'' (genuine, informed by revelation). This does not eliminate physical expressions of worship but insists that they be animated by the Spirit and grounded in truth.'),
  (25, 'The woman saith unto him, I know that Messias cometh, which is called Christ: when he is come, he will tell us all things.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ ἡ γυνή Οἶδα ὅτι Μεσσίας ἔρχεται ὁ λεγόμενος Χριστός ὅταν ἔλθῃ ἐκεῖνος ἀναγγελεῖ ἡμῖν πάντα',
   'legei autō hē gynē Oida hoti Messias erchetai ho legomenos Christos hotan elthē ekeinos anangelei hēmin panta',
   '''Messias'' (Messias — the Aramaic/Hebrew form, transliterated into Greek; John translates for his readers: ''which is called Christ,'' Christos, the Anointed One). The Samaritan expectation was of the Taheb — the ''Returning One'' or ''Restorer'' based on Deuteronomy 18:15-18 (a prophet like Moses). ''He will tell us all things'' (anangelei hēmin panta — he will announce, declare everything to us). The woman recognises that the kind of comprehensive knowledge Jesus has demonstrated is a messianic attribute. She is on the threshold of faith.',
   NULL),
  (26, 'Jesus saith unto her, I that speak unto thee am he.',
   'λέγει αὐτῇ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἐγώ εἰμι ὁ λαλῶν σοι',
   'legei autē ho Iēsous Egō eimi ho lalōn soi',
   '''I that speak unto thee am he'' (egō eimi ho lalōn soi — I am, the one speaking to you). ''Egō eimi'' (I am) — the first explicit messianic self-identification in John. This is the formula that echoes the divine name (Exodus 3:14: ''I AM THAT I AM'') and will recur throughout the Gospel (6:35; 8:12, 24, 28, 58; 10:7, 11; 11:25; 14:6; 15:1; 18:5-6). Remarkably, Jesus makes this disclosure not to a Jewish leader or his own disciples but to a Samaritan woman of questionable reputation — the gospel is for all.',
   'Jesus'' self-revelation to the Samaritan woman is theologically remarkable: (1) He reveals his messiahship to a Samaritan before doing so openly in Jerusalem. (2) The formula ''egō eimi'' carries overtones of the divine name — ''I AM'' (Exodus 3:14). (3) He reveals himself to the most unlikely person — a woman, a Samaritan, an outcast — demonstrating that grace transcends all human boundaries. (4) In the Synoptics, Jesus commands secrecy about his messiahship (the ''messianic secret''); in John, he reveals it freely to this woman, suggesting that Samaria is a safer context for this disclosure than Jerusalem, where political messianism could be explosive.'),
  (27, 'And upon this came his disciples, and marvelled that he talked with the woman: yet no man said, What seekest thou? or, Why talkest thou with her?',
   'καὶ ἐπὶ τούτῳ ἦλθον οἱ μαθηταὶ αὐτοῦ καὶ ἐθαύμασαν ὅτι μετὰ γυναικὸς ἐλάλει οὐδεὶς μέντοι εἶπεν Τί ζητεῖς ἢ Τί λαλεῖς μετ᾽ αὐτῆς',
   'kai epi toutō ēlthon hoi mathētai autou kai ethaumasan hoti meta gynaikos elalei oudeis mentoi eipen Ti zēteis ē Ti laleis met autēs',
   '''Marvelled'' (ethaumasan — were astonished, amazed). The disciples'' surprise reveals the cultural norms Jesus was breaking: a rabbi speaking with a woman in public was considered improper. The Talmud warned: ''One should not talk with a woman on the street, not even with his own wife'' (Berakhot 43b). Yet they dare not question him — their growing awareness of his authority restrains them.',
   NULL),
  (28, 'The woman then left her waterpot, and went her way into the city, and saith to the men,',
   'ἀφῆκεν οὖν τὴν ὑδρίαν αὐτῆς ἡ γυνὴ καὶ ἀπῆλθεν εἰς τὴν πόλιν καὶ λέγει τοῖς ἀνθρώποις',
   'aphēken oun tēn hydrian autēs hē gynē kai apēlthen eis tēn polin kai legei tois anthrōpois',
   '''Left her waterpot'' (aphēken tēn hydrian — she abandoned her water jar). This small detail is significant: (1) she forgot her original errand in her excitement, (2) she has found ''living water'' and no longer needs the jar, (3) she left it for Jesus to drink — an act of hospitality. ''Went into the city'' — the woman who came alone at noon to avoid people now goes to the people. Encounter with Jesus transforms shame into testimony.',
   NULL),
  (29, 'Come, see a man, which told me all things that ever I did: is not this the Christ?',
   'Δεῦτε ἴδετε ἄνθρωπον ὃς εἶπέν μοι πάντα ὅσα ἐποίησα μήτι οὗτός ἐστιν ὁ Χριστός',
   'Deute idete anthrōpon hos eipen moi panta hosa epoiēsa mēti houtos estin ho Christos',
   '''Come, see'' (deute idete — come, look; cf. 1:39, 46: ''Come and see'' — the invitation that creates disciples). ''Told me all things that ever I did'' — an overstatement (he told her about her husbands), but her point is that he knew her completely. ''Is not this the Christ?'' (mēti houtos estin ho Christos — the particle mēti expects a tentative negative but hopes for a positive: ''This couldn''t be the Christ, could it?''). She does not dogmatically proclaim but invitingly questions — the most effective evangelism often begins with a question rather than a declaration.',
   NULL),
  (30, 'Then they went out of the city, and came unto him.',
   'ἐξῆλθον ἐκ τῆς πόλεως καὶ ἤρχοντο πρὸς αὐτόν',
   'exēlthon ek tēs poleōs kai ērchonto pros auton',
   'The imperfect tense (ērchonto — they were coming) suggests a continuous stream of Samaritans heading toward Jesus. One woman''s testimony sets in motion a communal response — the harvest that Jesus will describe in vv.35-38.',
   NULL),
  (31, 'In the mean while his disciples prayed him, saying, Master, eat.',
   'ἐν δὲ τῷ μεταξὺ ἠρώτων αὐτὸν οἱ μαθηταὶ λέγοντες Ῥαββί φάγε',
   'en de tō metaxy ērōtōn auton hoi mathētai legontes Rhabbi phage',
   'While the Samaritans are on their way, the disciples urge Jesus to eat. This sets up another Johannine misunderstanding: the disciples think of physical food; Jesus speaks of spiritual nourishment.',
   NULL),
  (32, 'But he said unto them, I have meat to eat that ye know not of.',
   'ὁ δὲ εἶπεν αὐτοῖς Ἐγὼ βρῶσιν ἔχω φαγεῖν ἣν ὑμεῖς οὐκ οἴδατε',
   'ho de eipen autois Egō brōsin echō phagein hēn hymeis ouk oidate',
   '''I have meat to eat that ye know not of'' (brōsin echō phagein — I have food to eat). Another level-shift from physical to spiritual, like ''living water'' (v.10) and ''born again'' (3:3). Jesus'' deepest satisfaction comes not from food but from doing the Father''s will. The disciples'' bewilderment (v.33) parallels the woman''s confusion about living water.',
   NULL),
  (33, 'Therefore said the disciples one to another, Hath any man brought him ought to eat?',
   'ἔλεγον οὖν οἱ μαθηταὶ πρὸς ἀλλήλους Μή τις ἤνεγκεν αὐτῷ φαγεῖν',
   'elegon oun hoi mathētai pros allēlous Mē tis ēnenken autō phagein',
   'The disciples'' literal misunderstanding (''Did someone bring him food?'') follows the pattern of Nicodemus (3:4), the Samaritan woman (4:11, 15), and later audiences (6:52). Physical thinking must give way to spiritual perception.',
   NULL),
  (34, 'Jesus saith unto them, My meat is to do the will of him that sent me, and to finish his work.',
   'λέγει αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἐμὸν βρῶμά ἐστιν ἵνα ποιῶ τὸ θέλημα τοῦ πέμψαντός με καὶ τελειώσω αὐτοῦ τὸ ἔργον',
   'legei autois ho Iēsous Emon brōma estin hina poiō to thelēma tou pempsantos me kai teleiōsō autou to ergon',
   '''My meat'' (emon brōma — my food, my nourishment). ''To do the will of him that sent me'' (poiō to thelēma tou pempsantos me — to do the will of the one who sent me). ''To finish his work'' (teleiōsō autou to ergon — to complete, bring to perfection his work). Jesus'' life is entirely oriented toward the Father''s mission. ''Finish'' (teleiōsō — to bring to completion, perfection) anticipates the cross: ''It is finished'' (tetelestai, 19:30). The conversation with the Samaritan woman was not a detour but a direct expression of the Father''s will — this is the ''work'' that nourishes Jesus.',
   NULL),
  (35, 'Say not ye, There are yet four months, and then cometh harvest? behold, I say unto you, Lift up your eyes, and look on the fields; for they are white already to harvest.',
   'οὐχ ὑμεῖς λέγετε ὅτι Ἔτι τετράμηνός ἐστιν καὶ ὁ θερισμὸς ἔρχεται ἰδοὺ λέγω ὑμῖν ἐπάρατε τοὺς ὀφθαλμοὺς ὑμῶν καὶ θεάσασθε τὰς χώρας ὅτι λευκαί εἰσιν πρὸς θερισμὸν ἤδη',
   'ouch hymeis legete hoti Eti tetramēnos estin kai ho therismos erchetai idou legō hymin eparate tous ophthalmous hymōn kai theasasthe tas chōras hoti leukai eisin pros therismon ēdē',
   '''Four months, and then cometh harvest'' — possibly a proverb about patience, or a literal time reference (if it is December, harvest would come in April). Jesus shatters the conventional timeline: ''Look on the fields'' — the Samaritans streaming from the city toward him are the ''white'' harvest. ''White already'' (leukai ēdē — already white, ready). The spiritual harvest does not follow the calendar of nature; it is ready now. ''Lift up your eyes'' — the disciples are looking at food; Jesus tells them to look at people.',
   NULL),
  (36, 'And he that reapeth receiveth wages, and gathereth fruit unto life eternal: that both he that soweth and he that reapeth may rejoice together.',
   'ὁ θερίζων μισθὸν λαμβάνει καὶ συνάγει καρπὸν εἰς ζωὴν αἰώνιον ἵνα ὁ σπείρων ὁμοῦ χαίρῃ καὶ ὁ θερίζων',
   'ho therizōn misthon lambanei kai synagei karpon eis zōēn aiōnion hina ho speirōn homou chairē kai ho therizōn',
   '''Receiveth wages'' (misthon lambanei — receives reward). ''Gathereth fruit unto life eternal'' (synagei karpon eis zōēn aiōnion — collects fruit for eternal life). ''That both he that soweth and he that reapeth may rejoice together'' — the sower (the OT prophets, John the Baptist, Jesus himself) and the reaper (the disciples, later the church) share in the joy of the harvest. No competition between labourers — all share the reward and rejoicing.',
   NULL),
  (37, 'And herein is that saying true, One soweth, and another reapeth.',
   'ἐν γὰρ τούτῳ ὁ λόγος ἐστὶν ὁ ἀληθινός ὅτι Ἄλλος ἐστὶν ὁ σπείρων καὶ ἄλλος ὁ θερίζων',
   'en gar toutō ho logos estin ho alēthinos hoti Allos estin ho speirōn kai allos ho therizōn',
   'The proverb ''One soweth, and another reapeth'' usually carried a negative sense (you labour and someone else benefits). Jesus redeems it: in God''s economy, sowing and reaping are complementary, not competitive. The sower does not lose when another reaps — both share the joy (v.36).',
   NULL),
  (38, 'I sent you to reap that whereon ye bestowed no labour: other men laboured, and ye are entered into their labours.',
   'ἐγὼ ἀπέστειλα ὑμᾶς θερίζειν ὃ οὐχ ὑμεῖς κεκοπιάκατε ἄλλοι κεκοπιάκασιν καὶ ὑμεῖς εἰς τὸν κόπον αὐτῶν εἰσεληλύθατε',
   'egō apesteila hymas therizein ho ouch hymeis kekopiakate alloi kekopiaksin kai hymeis eis ton kopon autōn eiselēlythate',
   '''Other men laboured'' (alloi kekopiaksin — others have toiled). ''Ye are entered into their labours'' — the disciples inherit the work of Moses, the prophets, John the Baptist, and Jesus himself. The harvest they will reap in Samaria (and later worldwide) was prepared by centuries of divine sowing. The verb kopiō (to labour, toil) is the same used of Jesus'' weariness in v.6 — he is the ultimate sower who labours so that others may reap.',
   NULL),
  (39, 'And many of the Samaritans of that city believed on him for the saying of the woman, which testified, He told me all that ever I did.',
   'ἐκ δὲ τῆς πόλεως ἐκείνης πολλοὶ ἐπίστευσαν εἰς αὐτὸν τῶν Σαμαρειτῶν διὰ τὸν λόγον τῆς γυναικὸς μαρτυρούσης ὅτι Εἶπέν μοι πάντα ἃ ἐποίησα',
   'ek de tēs poleōs ekeinēs polloi episteusan eis auton tōn Samareitōn dia ton logon tēs gynaikos martyrousēs hoti Eipen moi panta ha epoiēsa',
   '''Believed on him'' (episteusan eis auton — believed into him). ''For the saying of the woman'' (dia ton logon tēs gynaikos — because of the word/testimony of the woman). ''Which testified'' (martyrousēs — bearing witness; the same verb used of John the Baptist''s testimony, 1:7, 15). The woman becomes the first evangelist in John''s Gospel — and she evangelises Samaritans, the despised outsiders. Her testimony is effective because it is personal and authentic: ''He told me all that ever I did.''',
   NULL),
  (40, 'So when the Samaritans were come unto him, they besought him that he would tarry with them: and he abode there two days.',
   'ὡς οὖν ἦλθον πρὸς αὐτὸν οἱ Σαμαρεῖται ἠρώτων αὐτὸν μεῖναι παρ᾽ αὐτοῖς καὶ ἔμεινεν ἐκεῖ δύο ἡμέρας',
   'hōs oun ēlthon pros auton hoi Samareitai ērōtōn auton meinai par autois kai emeinen ekei duo hēmeras',
   '''Besought him'' (ērōtōn — kept asking, imperfect: persistent request). ''Tarry with them'' (meinai par autois — remain, abide with them). ''Two days'' — Jesus, a Jew, stays with Samaritans for two days, eating and teaching. This two-day stay produces a deeper faith than signs alone could produce (v.42). The verb ''abode'' (emeinen — remained) is a key Johannine word (15:4-10: ''Abide in me'').',
   NULL),
  (41, 'And many more believed because of his own word;',
   'καὶ πολλῷ πλείους ἐπίστευσαν διὰ τὸν λόγον αὐτοῦ',
   'kai pollō pleious episteusan dia ton logon autou',
   '''Many more'' (pollō pleious — far more, considerably more). ''Because of his own word'' (dia ton logon autou — because of his word). The progression: first they believed because of the woman''s testimony (v.39), then ''many more'' because of Jesus'' own word. Second-hand testimony brings them to Jesus; direct encounter with Jesus deepens and multiplies faith. The pattern is paradigmatic for evangelism: human testimony leads to personal encounter.',
   NULL),
  (42, 'And said unto the woman, Now we believe, not because of thy saying: for we have heard him ourselves, and know that this is indeed the Christ, the Saviour of the world.',
   'τῇ τε γυναικὶ ἔλεγον ὅτι Οὐκέτι διὰ τὴν σὴν λαλιὰν πιστεύομεν αὐτοὶ γὰρ ἀκηκόαμεν καὶ οἴδαμεν ὅτι οὗτός ἐστιν ἀληθῶς ὁ σωτὴρ τοῦ κόσμου ὁ Χριστός',
   'tē te gynaiki elegon hoti Ouketi dia tēn sēn lalian pisteuomen autoi gar akēkoamen kai oidamen hoti houtos estin alēthōs ho sōtēr tou kosmou ho Christos',
   '''The Saviour of the world'' (ho sōtēr tou kosmou) — this title occurs only here and in 1 John 4:14 in the entire Bible. Samaritans — despised outsiders — are the first to confess Jesus not merely as Messiah but as the Saviour of the whole world. ''We have heard him ourselves'' (autoi akēkoamen — we ourselves have heard; perfect tense: we have heard and continue to know). ''We know'' (oidamen — we know with certainty). Their faith has moved from secondhand (the woman''s testimony) to firsthand (Jesus'' own word) — from ''Is not this the Christ?'' (v.29) to ''This is indeed the Christ, the Saviour of the world.''',
   'The Samaritan confession — ''the Saviour of the world'' — is theologically climactic. (1) The title transcends Jewish messianism: Jesus is not merely Israel''s Messiah but the world''s Saviour. (2) The Samaritans, whom the Jews despised, recognise what Jerusalem''s leaders will reject. (3) The title ''Saviour of the world'' was used by Roman emperors (soter tou kosmou was applied to Augustus and others); these Samaritans confess that the true Saviour is not Caesar but Jesus. (4) The progression from 1:29 (''Lamb of God, which taketh away the sin of the world'') through 3:16 (''God so loved the world'') to 4:42 (''the Saviour of the world'') establishes the universal scope of Jesus'' mission.'),
  (43, 'Now after two days he departed thence, and went into Galilee.',
   'μετὰ δὲ τὰς δύο ἡμέρας ἐξῆλθεν ἐκεῖθεν καὶ ἀπῆλθεν εἰς τὴν Γαλιλαίαν',
   'meta de tas duo hēmeras exēlthen ekeithen kai apēlthen eis tēn Galilaian',
   'After the two days in Samaria, Jesus continues to Galilee. The narrative transitions from the Samaritan harvest to the Galilean response, and from the conversation about worship to the second sign at Cana.',
   NULL),
  (44, 'For Jesus himself testified, that a prophet hath no honour in his own country.',
   'αὐτὸς γὰρ Ἰησοῦς ἐμαρτύρησεν ὅτι προφήτης ἐν τῇ ἰδίᾳ πατρίδι τιμὴν οὐκ ἔχει',
   'autos gar Iēsous emartyrēsen hoti prophētēs en tē idia patridi timēn ouk echei',
   '''A prophet hath no honour in his own country'' (prophētēs en tē idia patridi timēn ouk echei). In the Synoptics, ''his own country'' is Nazareth (Mark 6:1-6; Luke 4:24). In John''s context, ''his own country'' may refer to Judaea (where he was rejected) or Galilee (where the reception will be superficial, based on signs rather than faith). The Samaritans — outsiders — received him with genuine faith; his own people will require signs.',
   NULL),
  (45, 'Then when he was come into Galilee, the Galilaeans received him, having seen all the things that he did at Jerusalem at the feast: for they also went unto the feast.',
   'ὅτε οὖν ἦλθεν εἰς τὴν Γαλιλαίαν ἐδέξαντο αὐτὸν οἱ Γαλιλαῖοι πάντα ἑωρακότες ἃ ἐποίησεν ἐν Ἱεροσολύμοις ἐν τῇ ἑορτῇ καὶ αὐτοὶ γὰρ ἦλθον εἰς τὴν ἑορτήν',
   'hote oun ēlthen eis tēn Galilaian edexanto auton hoi Galilaioi panta heōrakotes ha epoiēsen en Hierosolymois en tē heortē kai autoi gar ēlthon eis tēn heortēn',
   '''Received him'' (edexanto — welcomed him). The Galileans welcome Jesus, but their reception is based on having seen his miracles at Jerusalem (cf. 2:23). This is sign-based faith — genuine but shallow. The contrast with the Samaritans is deliberate: the Samaritans believed because of Jesus'' word (vv.41-42); the Galileans are impressed by what they saw. Jesus will address this directly in v.48.',
   NULL),
  (46, 'So Jesus came again into Cana of Galilee, where he made the water wine. And there was a certain nobleman, whose son was sick at Capernaum.',
   'ἦλθεν οὖν ὁ Ἰησοῦς πάλιν εἰς τὴν Κανᾶ τῆς Γαλιλαίας ὅπου ἐποίησεν τὸ ὕδωρ οἶνον καὶ ἦν τις βασιλικὸς οὗ ὁ υἱὸς ἠσθένει ἐν Καπερναούμ',
   'ēlthen oun ho Iēsous palin eis tēn Kana tēs Galilaias hopou epoiēsen to hydōr oinon kai ēn tis basilikos hou ho huios ēsthenei en Kapernaoum',
   '''Where he made the water wine'' — John connects the second sign back to the first (2:1-11). ''A certain nobleman'' (basilikos — a royal official, someone connected to the court, likely of Herod Antipas). ''Whose son was sick'' (hou ho huios ēsthenei — whose son was ailing, weak). Capernaum is about 20 miles from Cana. The official''s desperation drives him to make the journey.',
   NULL),
  (47, 'When he heard that Jesus was come out of Judaea into Galilee, he went unto him, and besought him that he would come down, and heal his son: for he was at the point of death.',
   'οὗτος ἀκούσας ὅτι Ἰησοῦς ἥκει ἐκ τῆς Ἰουδαίας εἰς τὴν Γαλιλαίαν ἀπῆλθεν πρὸς αὐτὸν καὶ ἠρώτα αὐτὸν ἵνα καταβῇ καὶ ἰάσηται αὐτοῦ τὸν υἱόν ἤμελλεν γὰρ ἀποθνήσκειν',
   'houtos akousas hoti Iēsous hēkei ek tēs Ioudaias eis tēn Galilaian apēlthen pros auton kai ērōta auton hina katabē kai iasētai autou ton huion ēmellen gar apothnēskein',
   '''Besought him'' (ērōta — kept asking, imperfect: persistent request). ''Come down'' (katabē — descend; Cana is in the hills, Capernaum on the lake shore). ''At the point of death'' (ēmellen apothnēskein — was about to die). The nobleman''s faith has a critical limitation: he believes Jesus must be physically present to heal. Jesus will challenge and deepen this faith.',
   NULL),
  (48, 'Then said Jesus unto him, Except ye see signs and wonders, ye will not believe.',
   'εἶπεν οὖν ὁ Ἰησοῦς πρὸς αὐτόν Ἐὰν μὴ σημεῖα καὶ τέρατα ἴδητε οὐ μὴ πιστεύσητε',
   'eipen oun ho Iēsous pros auton Ean mē sēmeia kai terata idēte ou mē pisteusēte',
   '''Except ye see signs and wonders'' (ean mē sēmeia kai terata idēte — unless you [plural] see signs and wonders). The plural ''ye'' addresses not just the nobleman but the Galileans generally (cf. v.45). ''Signs and wonders'' (sēmeia kai terata) — John usually says ''signs'' alone; adding ''wonders'' echoes the Exodus language (Exodus 7:3; Deuteronomy 6:22) and implies a faith that demands spectacular evidence. Jesus challenges the Galileans'' dependence on miracles — the Samaritans believed without them (v.41).',
   NULL),
  (49, 'The nobleman saith unto him, Sir, come down ere my child die.',
   'λέγει πρὸς αὐτὸν ὁ βασιλικός Κύριε κατάβηθι πρὶν ἀποθανεῖν τὸ παιδίον μου',
   'legei pros auton ho basilikos Kyrie katabēthi prin apothanein to paidion mou',
   '''Sir, come down ere my child die'' (Kyrie katabēthi — Lord, come down). The nobleman does not argue theology; he pleads as a father. ''My child'' (to paidion mou — my little child; the diminutive conveys tenderness). His faith is imperfect (he still thinks Jesus must be present) but genuine (he persists despite Jesus'' rebuke). Desperation can be a pathway to deeper faith.',
   NULL),
  (50, 'Jesus saith unto him, Go thy way; thy son liveth. And the man believed the word that Jesus had spoken unto him, and he went his way.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Πορεύου ὁ υἱός σου ζῇ καὶ ἐπίστευσεν ὁ ἄνθρωπος τῷ λόγῳ ᾧ εἶπεν αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς καὶ ἐπορεύετο',
   'legei autō ho Iēsous Poreuou ho huios sou zē kai episteusen ho anthrōpos tō logō hō eipen autō ho Iēsous kai eporeueto',
   '''Go thy way; thy son liveth'' (poreuou ho huios sou zē — go, your son lives; present tense: is living right now). ''The man believed the word'' (episteusen tō logō — believed the word; dative: trusted in the word). This is the critical moment: the nobleman believed Jesus'' word without seeing the result. He must walk 20 miles back to Capernaum with nothing but Jesus'' word to sustain him. His faith has been elevated from sign-based (''come down and heal'') to word-based (''he believed the word''). This is the faith Jesus commends: trusting his word without sight (cf. 20:29).',
   'The nobleman''s faith journey models the progression John seeks for all readers: (1) He hears about Jesus (v.47) — report-based interest. (2) He comes to Jesus (v.47) — action on incomplete faith. (3) He asks for a miracle (v.47) — sign-dependent faith. (4) He believes Jesus'' word (v.50) — word-based faith. (5) His faith is confirmed (v.53) — experience validates faith. (6) His whole house believes (v.53) — faith becomes communal. The key transition is step 4: believing the word without seeing the sign. This is the faith John''s Gospel seeks to produce: ''blessed are they that have not seen, and yet have believed'' (20:29).'),
  (51, 'And as he was now going down, his servants met him, and told him, saying, Thy son liveth.',
   'ἤδη δὲ αὐτοῦ καταβαίνοντος οἱ δοῦλοι αὐτοῦ ἀπήντησαν αὐτῷ καὶ ἀπήγγειλαν λέγοντες ὅτι Ὁ παῖς σου ζῇ',
   'ēdē de autou katabainontos hoi douloi autou apēntēsan autō kai apēngeilan legontes hoti Ho pais sou zē',
   '''Going down'' (katabainontos — descending; Cana to Capernaum is downhill). ''Thy son liveth'' (ho pais sou zē — your boy lives; the servants use the same words Jesus spoke, zē: lives, present tense). The servants'' report confirms Jesus'' word. The healing was instantaneous and remote — Jesus did not need to be present. This sign reveals Jesus'' authority over space: his word operates at a distance.',
   NULL),
  (52, 'Then enquired he of them the hour when he began to amend. And they said unto him, Yesterday at the seventh hour the fever left him.',
   'ἐπύθετο οὖν παρ᾽ αὐτῶν τὴν ὥραν ἐν ᾗ κομψότερον ἔσχεν καὶ εἶπον αὐτῷ ὅτι Χθὲς ὥραν ἑβδόμην ἀφῆκεν αὐτὸν ὁ πυρετός',
   'epytheto oun par autōn tēn hōran en hē kompsoteron eschen kai eipon autō hoti Chthes hōran hebdomēn aphēken auton ho pyretos',
   '''The seventh hour'' (hōran hebdomēn — 1 PM by Jewish reckoning, or 7 PM by Roman). ''The fever left him'' (aphēken auton ho pyretos — the fever released him, let him go). The nobleman inquires about the exact hour — he wants to verify the connection between Jesus'' word and the healing. The correlation is exact: the moment Jesus spoke, the boy was healed. This precision eliminates coincidence and confirms divine causation.',
   NULL),
  (53, 'So the father knew that it was at the same hour, in the which Jesus said unto him, Thy son liveth: and himself believed, and his whole house.',
   'ἔγνω οὖν ὁ πατὴρ ὅτι ἐν ἐκείνῃ τῇ ὥρᾳ ἐν ᾗ εἶπεν αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ὁ υἱός σου ζῇ καὶ ἐπίστευσεν αὐτὸς καὶ ἡ οἰκία αὐτοῦ ὅλη',
   'egnō oun ho patēr hoti en ekeinē tē hōra en hē eipen autō ho Iēsous Ho huios sou zē kai episteusen autos kai hē oikia autou holē',
   '''At the same hour'' (en ekeinē tē hōra — at that very hour). ''Himself believed'' (episteusen autos — he himself believed). ''And his whole house'' (hē oikia autou holē — his entire household). The nobleman''s faith deepens: from initial request (v.47) to trusting the word (v.50) to confirmed faith (v.53). ''His whole house'' — a household conversion (cf. Acts 10:2; 16:15, 31-34; 18:8). The sign produces not just individual but communal faith.',
   NULL),
  (54, 'This is again the second miracle that Jesus did, when he was come out of Judaea into Galilee.',
   'τοῦτο πάλιν δεύτερον σημεῖον ἐποίησεν ὁ Ἰησοῦς ἐλθὼν ἐκ τῆς Ἰουδαίας εἰς τὴν Γαλιλαίαν',
   'touto palin deuteron sēmeion epoiēsen ho Iēsous elthōn ek tēs Ioudaias eis tēn Galilaian',
   '''The second miracle'' (deuteron sēmeion — the second sign). John counts Galilean signs: the first was water to wine at Cana (2:11); this is the second, also connected to Cana. Between these two Galilean signs, Jesus performed signs in Jerusalem (2:23; 3:2) which John does not number. The numbering may indicate a ''signs source'' that John used, or simply John''s literary structure connecting Cana-to-Cana. Both Cana signs involve transformation at a distance: water to wine, death to life.',
   NULL)
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 4;

-- Step 3: Insert word studies
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, usage_notes, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.usage_notes, ws.word_order
FROM (VALUES
  ('ὕδωρ ζῶν', 'hydōr zōn', 'G5204/G2198',
   'Living water — fresh, flowing spring water; metaphorically, the water of eternal life, the Holy Spirit.',
   'In the OT, ''living water'' (mayim chayyim) refers to fresh, flowing spring water as opposed to stagnant cistern water (Genesis 26:19; Leviticus 14:5; Jeremiah 2:13). God is ''the fountain of living waters'' (Jeremiah 2:13; 17:13). Jesus claims to give what only God can give. In 7:38-39, John identifies the living water as the Holy Spirit: ''He that believeth on me... out of his belly shall flow rivers of living water. But this spake he of the Spirit.'' The living water is internal (''in him a well,'' v.14), inexhaustible (''shall never thirst''), and eternal (''springing up into everlasting life'').',
   1),
  ('πηγή', 'pēgē', 'G4077',
   'Spring, fountain, well; a source of flowing water; metaphorically, an inner source of spiritual life.',
   'Pēgē refers to a spring or natural water source (as opposed to a cistern, which collects rainwater). In v.6, it refers to Jacob''s well. In v.14, Jesus promises that the living water ''shall be in him a pēgē of water springing up into everlasting life.'' The believer becomes a spring — not just a container but a source. The image appears in Revelation 7:17 (''the Lamb... shall lead them unto living fountains of waters'') and 21:6 (''I will give unto him that is athirst of the fountain of the water of life freely'').',
   2),
  ('προσκυνέω', 'proskyneō', 'G4352',
   'To worship, to bow down before, to do obeisance, to prostrate oneself in reverence.',
   'From pros (toward) + kyneō (to kiss). Originally meant to kiss the ground before a deity or king. In John 4, proskyneō occurs 10 times (vv.20-24), making it the most concentrated discussion of worship in the Gospels. True worship is ''in spirit and in truth'' (v.23-24) — not defined by location (Gerizim or Jerusalem) but by the nature of God himself (''God is Spirit''). The Father ''seeketh'' (zētei) true worshippers — the only place in Scripture where God is said to seek worshippers.',
   3),
  ('ἐγώ εἰμι', 'egō eimi', 'G1473/G1510',
   'I am — the divine self-identification formula, echoing the name God revealed to Moses at the burning bush.',
   'In v.26, Jesus says ''egō eimi, ho lalōn soi'' (''I am, the one speaking to you''). This is the first of many egō eimi declarations in John. Some are predicated (''I am the bread of life,'' 6:35; ''I am the light,'' 8:12; etc.), while others are absolute (8:24, 28, 58; 13:19; 18:5-6). The absolute ''I am'' echoes Exodus 3:14 (''I AM THAT I AM'') and Isaiah 43:10-11 (''I am he... I, even I, am the LORD''). Jesus'' messianic self-revelation to the Samaritan woman uses this divine formula.',
   4),
  ('σωτήρ', 'sōtēr', 'G4990',
   'Saviour, deliverer, preserver; one who rescues from danger or destruction.',
   'The Samaritans confess Jesus as ''the Saviour of the world'' (ho sōtēr tou kosmou, v.42) — a title occurring only here and 1 John 4:14 in Scripture. In the OT, God alone is Saviour: ''I, even I, am the LORD; and beside me there is no saviour'' (Isaiah 43:11; cf. Hosea 13:4). To call Jesus ''Saviour of the world'' is to attribute to him a divine function. The title also contrasts with the Roman imperial cult, where emperors claimed the title sōtēr tou kosmou. The true Saviour is not Caesar but Christ.',
   5),
  ('θερισμός', 'therismos', 'G2326',
   'Harvest, reaping; the gathering of crops; metaphorically, the gathering of souls into the kingdom.',
   'From therizō (to reap, to harvest). Jesus uses the harvest metaphor (vv.35-38) to describe the spiritual readiness of the Samaritans. ''The fields are white already to harvest'' — the spiritual harvest is ripe now, not in four months. The harvest imagery appears throughout Scripture: Joel 3:13 (judgment), Matthew 9:37-38 (''the harvest truly is plenteous, but the labourers are few''), Matthew 13:39 (''the harvest is the end of the world''), Revelation 14:15 (the final reaping). Here the emphasis is on present opportunity, not future judgment.',
   6),
  ('βασιλικός', 'basilikos', 'G937',
   'Royal official, nobleman, one connected to the king''s court; from basileus (king).',
   'The basilikos was an officer in the service of Herod Antipas (tetrarch of Galilee). Some identify him with Chuza, Herod''s steward, whose wife Joanna later followed Jesus (Luke 8:3). The term indicates social standing and political connection — this is not a peasant but a man of rank and resources. Yet his son''s illness has brought him to the point of desperate faith. Social position provides no immunity from suffering, and suffering can be the doorway to faith.',
   7),
  ('λόγος', 'logos', 'G3056',
   'Word, saying, message, statement; the expressed thought or utterance; in John, the divine self-expression.',
   'In v.50, ''the man believed the word (tō logō) that Jesus had spoken.'' The logos Jesus speaks has creative power — it heals at a distance, just as God''s word created the universe (Genesis 1:3; Psalm 33:6; Hebrews 11:3). The connection to John 1:1 (''In the beginning was the Logos'') is deliberate: the Word who made all things (1:3) speaks a word that restores life. To believe ''the word'' is to trust in the person who speaks it — the Logos incarnate.',
   8)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, usage_notes, word_order)
CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
  SELECT v2.id FROM verses v2
  JOIN chapters c2 ON v2.chapter_id = c2.id
  JOIN books b2 ON c2.book_id = b2.id
  WHERE b2.name = 'John' AND c2.chapter_number = 4
  AND v2.verse_number = CASE ws.word_order
    WHEN 1 THEN 10
    WHEN 2 THEN 14
    WHEN 3 THEN 24
    WHEN 4 THEN 26
    WHEN 5 THEN 42
    WHEN 6 THEN 35
    WHEN 7 THEN 46
    WHEN 8 THEN 50
  END
) v;

-- Step 4: Insert cross-references
INSERT INTO cross_references (verse_id, reference, context, ref_order)
SELECT v.id, cr.referenced_verse, cr.note, ROW_NUMBER() OVER ()::int
FROM (VALUES
  -- v.4: Must needs go through Samaria
  (4, 'Luke 9:51-56', 'parallel', 'Jesus passes through Samaria — the disciples want fire from heaven; Jesus rebukes them'),
  (4, 'Acts 1:8', 'thematic', '''Ye shall be witnesses... in Samaria'' — the Samaritan mission fulfils Jesus'' command'),
  (4, 'Acts 8:4-8', 'thematic', 'Philip preaches in Samaria — the harvest Jesus sowed is reaped by the early church'),
  -- v.6: Wearied with his journey
  (6, 'John 1:14', 'thematic', '''The Word was made flesh'' — Jesus'' weariness confirms his true humanity'),
  (6, 'Hebrews 4:15', 'thematic', '''Touched with the feeling of our infirmities'' — the incarnate Son truly experienced human weakness'),
  -- v.10: Living water
  (10, 'Jeremiah 2:13', 'allusion', '''They have forsaken me the fountain of living waters, and hewed them out broken cisterns'''),
  (10, 'Jeremiah 17:13', 'allusion', '''They that depart from me... have forsaken the LORD, the fountain of living waters'''),
  (10, 'Isaiah 12:3', 'prophecy', '''With joy shall ye draw water out of the wells of salvation'''),
  (10, 'Isaiah 55:1', 'thematic', '''Every one that thirsteth, come ye to the waters'''),
  (10, 'John 7:37-39', 'thematic', '''If any man thirst, let him come unto me, and drink'' — the Spirit as living water'),
  -- v.14: Well of water springing up
  (14, 'John 7:38-39', 'thematic', '''Out of his belly shall flow rivers of living water — this spake he of the Spirit'''),
  (14, 'Isaiah 44:3', 'prophecy', '''I will pour water upon him that is thirsty, and floods upon the dry ground'''),
  (14, 'Revelation 21:6', 'thematic', '''I will give unto him that is athirst of the fountain of the water of life freely'''),
  (14, 'Revelation 7:17', 'thematic', '''The Lamb... shall lead them unto living fountains of waters'''),
  -- v.18: Five husbands
  (18, 'John 2:24-25', 'thematic', '''He knew what was in man'' — Jesus'' supernatural knowledge of the human heart'),
  (18, '2 Kings 17:24-41', 'allusion', 'The foreign nations settled in Samaria brought their own gods — possible symbolic background'),
  -- v.22: Salvation is of the Jews
  (22, 'Romans 9:4-5', 'thematic', '''To whom pertaineth the adoption, and the glory, and the covenants... of whom as concerning the flesh Christ came'''),
  (22, 'Genesis 12:3', 'prophecy', '''In thee shall all families of the earth be blessed'' — salvation through Abraham''s seed'),
  (22, 'Isaiah 2:3', 'prophecy', '''Out of Zion shall go forth the law, and the word of the LORD from Jerusalem'''),
  -- v.23: Worship in spirit and truth
  (23, 'Philippians 3:3', 'thematic', '''We... worship God in the spirit, and rejoice in Christ Jesus, and have no confidence in the flesh'''),
  (23, 'Romans 12:1', 'thematic', '''Present your bodies a living sacrifice... your reasonable service'' — spiritual worship'),
  (23, 'Psalm 145:18', 'thematic', '''The LORD is nigh unto all them that call upon him... in truth'''),
  -- v.24: God is a Spirit
  (24, '1 John 1:5', 'thematic', '''God is light, and in him is no darkness at all'' — another ''God is'' statement'),
  (24, '1 John 4:8', 'thematic', '''God is love'' — the third great ''God is'' statement in John''s writings'),
  (24, 'Deuteronomy 4:15-19', 'thematic', '''Ye saw no manner of similitude'' — God has no physical form'),
  -- v.26: I that speak unto thee am he (ego eimi)
  (26, 'Exodus 3:14', 'allusion', '''I AM THAT I AM'' — the divine name echoed in Jesus'' ''I am'''),
  (26, 'John 8:58', 'thematic', '''Before Abraham was, I am'' — the absolute divine claim'),
  (26, 'John 18:5-6', 'thematic', '''I am he'' — the soldiers fall back at the divine self-identification'),
  (26, 'Isaiah 43:10-11', 'allusion', '''I am he... I, even I, am the LORD; and beside me there is no saviour'''),
  -- v.34: My meat is to do the will of him that sent me
  (34, 'John 5:30', 'thematic', '''I seek not mine own will, but the will of the Father which hath sent me'''),
  (34, 'John 6:38', 'thematic', '''I came down from heaven, not to do mine own will, but the will of him that sent me'''),
  (34, 'John 17:4', 'thematic', '''I have finished the work which thou gavest me to do'''),
  (34, 'John 19:30', 'thematic', '''It is finished'' — tetelestai: the work is completed'),
  -- v.35: Fields white to harvest
  (35, 'Matthew 9:37-38', 'parallel', '''The harvest truly is plenteous, but the labourers are few — pray ye therefore'''),
  (35, 'Luke 10:2', 'parallel', '''The harvest truly is great, but the labourers are few'''),
  -- v.42: Saviour of the world
  (42, '1 John 4:14', 'parallel', '''The Father sent the Son to be the Saviour of the world'' — the only other occurrence'),
  (42, 'John 1:29', 'thematic', '''The Lamb of God, which taketh away the sin of the world'' — universal scope'),
  (42, 'John 3:16-17', 'thematic', '''God so loved the world... that the world through him might be saved'''),
  (42, 'Isaiah 43:11', 'allusion', '''I, even I, am the LORD; and beside me there is no saviour'' — a divine title applied to Jesus'),
  -- v.44: A prophet hath no honour
  (44, 'Mark 6:4', 'parallel', '''A prophet is not without honour, but in his own country, and among his own kin'''),
  (44, 'Luke 4:24', 'parallel', '''No prophet is accepted in his own country'''),
  -- v.48: Signs and wonders
  (48, 'John 20:29', 'thematic', '''Blessed are they that have not seen, and yet have believed'' — faith without sight'),
  (48, '1 Corinthians 1:22', 'thematic', '''The Jews require a sign'' — the demand for miraculous proof'),
  -- v.50: Thy son liveth — believed the word
  (50, 'Matthew 8:8-10', 'parallel', 'The centurion: ''Speak the word only, and my servant shall be healed'' — faith in Jesus'' word at a distance'),
  (50, 'Psalm 107:20', 'allusion', '''He sent his word, and healed them'' — the healing power of God''s word'),
  -- v.53: His whole house believed
  (53, 'Acts 16:31-34', 'parallel', '''Believe on the Lord Jesus Christ, and thou shalt be saved, and thy house'' — household faith'),
  (53, 'Acts 10:2', 'parallel', 'Cornelius — ''a devout man, and one that feared God with all his house''')
) AS cr(verse_number, referenced_verse, relationship_type, note)
CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
  SELECT v2.id FROM verses v2
  JOIN chapters c2 ON v2.chapter_id = c2.id
  JOIN books b2 ON c2.book_id = b2.id
  WHERE b2.name = 'John' AND c2.chapter_number = 4 AND v2.verse_number = cr.verse_number
) v;

-- JOHN CHAPTER 4 — BACKFILL (additional word_studies + cross_references)

INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, w.original_word, w.transliteration, w.strongs_number, w.meaning, w.word_order
FROM verses v JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (4, 'ἔδει διέρχεσθαι διὰ τῆς Σαμαρείας', 'edei dierchesthai dia tēs Samareias', 'G1163/G1330/G4540', 'It was necessary to pass through Samaria — geographic shortcut yes, but dei (divine necessity) suggests theological purpose: salvation must come to the Samaritans.', 100),
  (5, 'Σιχάρ', 'Sichar', 'G4965', 'Sychar — likely modern Askar at the foot of Mt. Ebal; near ancient Shechem; rich patriarchal associations (Gen 12:6-7; 33:18-20).', 101),
  (6, 'πηγὴ τοῦ Ἰακὼβ', 'pēgē tou Iakōb', 'G4077/G2384', 'Jacob''s well — fed by spring; one of the few archaeologically certain sites in Israel; still produces water today (~135 ft deep).', 102),
  (6, 'κεκοπιακὼς', 'kekopiakōs', 'G2872', 'Wearied (perfect) — kopiaō: exhausting toil; full incarnational humanity — the Creator tires from his journey.', 103),
  (6, 'ὥρα ἕκτη', 'hōra hektē', 'G5610/G1623', 'Sixth hour — noon; unusual time for water-drawing (women came early/late); hints at her social ostracism.', 104),
  (7, 'γυνὴ ἐκ τῆς Σαμαρείας', 'gynē ek tēs Samareias', 'G1135/G4540', 'Samaritan woman — triple barrier: Samaritan, woman, immoral; Jesus crosses all three to evangelize.', 105),
  (9, 'οὐ συγχρῶνται', 'ou synchrōntai', 'G3756/G4798', 'Have no dealings with — synchraomai: share use of (vessels); centuries of mutual ritual avoidance.', 106),
  (9, 'Ἰουδαῖος', 'Ioudaios', 'G2453', 'Jew — woman identifies Jesus by accent/dress/manner; ironic since she will soon believe him to be Messiah.', 107),
  (10, 'τὴν δωρεὰν τοῦ θεοῦ', 'tēn dōrean tou theou', 'G1431/G2316', 'The gift of God — dōrea: free gift; Jesus offers what cannot be earned, only received.', 108),
  (11, 'τὸ φρέαρ βαθύ', 'to phrear bathy', 'G5421/G901', 'The well is deep — phrear: dug well/cistern; Jacob''s well is ~100+ ft deep; her literal-mindedness contrasts with Jesus''s spiritual meaning.', 109),
  (13, 'πᾶς ὁ πίνων', 'pas ho pinōn', 'G3956/G4095', 'Everyone drinking (present participle) — natural water leaves repeated thirst; living water permanently satisfies.', 110),
  (14, 'οὐ μὴ διψήσει εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα', 'ou mē dipsēsei eis ton aiōna', 'G3756/G3361/G1372/G165', 'Will never thirst into the age — emphatic double negative; eternal satisfaction.', 111),
  (14, 'πηγὴ ὕδατος ἁλλομένου', 'pēgē hydatos hallomenou', 'G4077/G5204/G242', 'Spring of water leaping up — hallomai: leap, gush; vivid image of internal spiritual artesian source.', 112),
  (16, 'ὕπαγε φώνησον τὸν ἄνδρα σου', 'hypage phōnēson ton andra sou', 'G5217/G5455/G435', '"Go call your husband" — Jesus pivots from intellectual discussion to her moral situation; the path to true worship goes through honest confrontation.', 113),
  (18, 'πέντε ἄνδρας ἔσχες', 'pente andras esches', 'G4002/G435/G2192', 'Five husbands you have had — likely combination of deaths and divorces; v.18 implies current cohabitation outside marriage.', 114),
  (19, 'προφήτης εἶ σύ', 'prophētēs ei sy', 'G4396/G4771', '"You are a prophet" — woman''s recognition; Samaritans expected the Taheb (Restorer-Prophet of Deut 18:15-18).', 115),
  (20, 'τὸ ὄρος τοῦτο', 'to oros touto', 'G3735', 'This mountain — Mt. Gerizim; Samaritan temple destroyed by John Hyrcanus 128 BC, but worship continued.', 116),
  (21, 'ἔρχεται ὥρα', 'erchetai hōra', 'G2064/G5610', 'An hour is coming — eschatological transition; new covenant worship transcends geography.', 117),
  (22, 'ἡ σωτηρία ἐκ τῶν Ἰουδαίων ἐστίν', 'hē sōtēria ek tōn Ioudaiōn estin', 'G4991/G2453', '"Salvation is from the Jews" — covenantal priority of Israel (Rom 9:4-5; 11:18); not exclusivist but historic-theological.', 118),
  (23, 'οἱ ἀληθινοὶ προσκυνηταὶ', 'hoi alēthinoi proskynētai', 'G228/G4353', 'True worshipers — alēthinos: real, genuine; defined by manner (spirit/truth), not location.', 119),
  (23, 'ἐν πνεύματι καὶ ἀληθείᾳ', 'en pneumati kai alētheia', 'G4151/G225', 'In spirit and truth — single sphere governed by both the Spirit and the truth (Christ); inward authentic worship.', 120),
  (24, 'πνεῦμα ὁ θεός', 'pneuma ho theos', 'G4151/G2316', '"God is spirit" — anarthrous predicate (qualitative); not "a spirit" but spirit by nature; ontological statement.', 121),
  (25, 'Μεσσίας... Χριστός', 'Messias... Christos', 'G3323/G5547', 'Messiah... Christ — Aramaic/Greek equivalents; even Samaritans (with truncated canon) expected the coming Anointed.', 122),
  (26, 'ἐγώ εἰμι', 'egō eimi', 'G1473/G1510', 'I AM — first explicit "I am" self-disclosure to a woman, a Samaritan, with morally compromised history; gospel order reversed.', 123),
  (27, 'ἐθαύμαζον ὅτι μετὰ γυναικὸς ἐλάλει', 'ethaumazon hoti meta gynaikos elalei', 'G2296/G1135/G2980', 'Marveled that he was speaking with a woman — rabbinic prohibition: "let no man talk with a woman in the street, no, not with his own wife".', 124),
  (28, 'ἀφῆκεν τὴν ὑδρίαν', 'aphēken tēn hydrian', 'G863/G5201', 'Left her water jar — symbolic detail: she abandons the lesser thirst for the greater task of witness.', 125),
  (29, 'μήτι οὗτός ἐστιν ὁ Χριστός', 'mēti houtos estin ho Christos', 'G3385/G5547', '"Could this be the Christ?" — tentative form (mēti expects "no" answer) shows her humility but also conviction.', 126),
  (32, 'βρῶσιν φαγεῖν', 'brōsin phagein', 'G1035/G5315', 'Food to eat — Jesus''s sustenance: doing the Father''s will (v.34) feeds him more than physical bread.', 127),
  (34, 'τελειώσω', 'teleiōsō', 'G5048', 'To complete (aorist subjunctive) — telos: bring to fullness; same root as tetelestai (19:30).', 128),
  (35, 'λευκαί', 'leukai', 'G3022', 'White — ripe grain heads turn pale yellow-white; mission readiness imagery.', 129),
  (36, 'μισθὸν λαμβάνει', 'misthon lambanei', 'G3408/G2983', 'Receives wages — kingdom labor has reward (Matt 5:12; 1 Cor 3:14); sower and reaper rejoice together.', 130),
  (38, 'ἄλλοι κεκοπιάκασιν', 'alloi kekopiakasin', 'G243/G2872', 'Others have labored — apostolic harvest depends on prior generations of OT prophets and pre-evangelistic groundwork.', 131),
  (42, 'τοῦ κόσμου', 'tou kosmou', 'G2889', 'Of the world — Samaritan villagers move beyond ethnic boundary: Jesus is Savior not just of Jews but of the kosmos.', 132),
  (44, 'ἐν τῇ ἰδίᾳ πατρίδι', 'en tē idia patridi', 'G2398/G3968', 'In his own homeland — generic dishonor of prophets; Jesus paradoxically welcomed in Galilee precisely because they had seen Jerusalem signs (v.45).', 133),
  (48, 'σημεῖα καὶ τέρατα', 'sēmeia kai terata', 'G4592/G5059', 'Signs and wonders — formulaic OT/NT pairing (Exod 7:3; Acts 2:22); Jesus laments faith dependent on miraculous validation.', 134),
  (50, 'ἐπίστευσεν ὁ ἄνθρωπος τῷ λόγῳ', 'episteusen ho anthrōpos tō logō', 'G4100/G3056', 'Believed the word — pure word-faith without sign; matures from sign-faith (v.48) to word-faith to full faith (v.53).', 135),
  (52, 'ὥραν ἑβδόμην', 'hōran hebdomēn', 'G5610/G1442', 'Seventh hour — 1 PM; precise time-stamp confirms supernatural healing was simultaneous with Jesus''s word.', 136),
  (53, 'ἐπίστευσεν αὐτὸς καὶ ἡ οἰκία αὐτοῦ ὅλη', 'episteusen autos kai hē oikia autou holē', 'G4100/G3614', 'Himself and his whole household believed — household conversion pattern (cf. Acts 16:31-34).', 137),
  (54, 'δεύτερον σημεῖον', 'deuteron sēmeion', 'G1208/G4592', 'Second sign — both Cana signs (water-to-wine, healing at distance) frame chapters 2-4; signs-source numbering.', 138)
) AS w(verse_number, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 4 AND v.verse_number = w.verse_number
ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;

